## What Each Template Does

### _helpers.tpl
Defines three reusable functions used across every template:
- bebeque-service.name — the chart name, max 63 characters
- bebeque-service.fullname — the Helm release name, used for
  all resource names
- bebeque-service.labels — common labels on every resource,
  includes chart version for traceability
- bebeque-service.selectorLabels — stable labels used in
  Deployment selectors and Service selectors. Never includes
  chart version because selector labels cannot change after
  a Deployment is created — Kubernetes rejects the update.

### deployment.yaml
The core template. Every service uses this regardless of type.
Key decisions:
- replicas comes from values — HPA and KEDA own it at runtime
- checksum/values annotation forces a rolling restart whenever
  any value changes, including env vars. Without this, a
  config change would not trigger a new rollout.
- Pod anti-affinity is a soft preference — two pods of the
  same service will prefer different nodes. Does not block
  scheduling if nodes are scarce.
- Ports block only renders when service.enabled is true.
  SQS workers have no HTTP port.
- Probes only render when probes.enabled is true.
  SQS workers have no health endpoint.
- terminationGracePeriodSeconds is set per service in values
  to match the SQS visibility timeout. biomass-ingestion uses
  30s. data-ingestion uses 120s. This gives workers time to
  finish processing messages before the pod is killed.

### service.yaml
Wrapped in a conditional. Only renders when service.enabled
is true. The two SQS workers — biomass-ingestion and
data-ingestion — set service.enabled: false and this file
produces nothing for them. Type is ClusterIP — traffic comes
from the ALB which lives outside the cluster in AWS.

### hpa.yaml
Wrapped in a conditional. Only renders when hpa.enabled is
true. analytics-api and notification-service use HPA on CPU.
The two SQS workers use KEDA instead and have hpa.enabled: false.
Uses autoscaling/v2 API — the current stable version.

### keda-scaledobject.yaml
Wrapped in a conditional. Only renders when keda.enabled is
true. biomass-ingestion and data-ingestion use this. Scales
on SQS queue depth. minReplicaCount: 0 means the worker scales
to zero when the queue is empty — no idle pods, no idle cost.
Uses identityOwner: pod so KEDA reads queue depth using the
pod's IRSA credentials. No static AWS keys.

### serviceaccount.yaml
Always renders. Carries the IRSA annotation that links the
Kubernetes service account to the AWS IAM role. This is how
pods get AWS credentials — EKS exchanges the pod's projected
service account token for temporary scoped AWS credentials.
No access keys anywhere.

### role.yaml
Always renders. An explicitly empty Kubernetes RBAC Role.
rules: [] means this service account has zero Kubernetes API
permissions. The Role exists to make that decision visible and
auditable rather than relying on the default behaviour.

### rolebinding.yaml
Always renders. Binds the service account to the empty Role.
Scoped to the namespace — cannot grant cross-namespace access.

### networkpolicy.yaml
Always renders. Default deny on ingress and egress with
explicit allow rules. Currently:
- Ingress: allow on the service port for HTTP services only
- Egress: allow all (tightened in Step 11)
This is the foundation. Step 11 adds OPA Gatekeeper and
tightens egress to only what each service needs.

