## Issues Encountered and Fixed

### Issue 1 — helm create failed due to space in folder name

The project folder is named Bebeque nergy Project with a
space. Running helm create helm/bebeque-service failed with:

  Error: GetFileAttributesEx ... The system cannot find
  the file specified.

Helm created the folder but then failed to verify it because
of the path with spaces. The fix was to create the folder
structure manually:

  New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path "helm/bebeque-service/templates"
  New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path "helm/bebeque-service/charts"
  New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path "helm/bebeque-service/values"

Then create every file individually with New-Item.

### Issue 2 — Old content in serviceaccount.yaml and service.yaml

During the first template render, the output showed commented-out
duplicate content from a previous version of both files. The
files had two versions merged together from earlier in the
session. Fixed by selecting all content in VS Code with Ctrl+A
and replacing with the clean version.

### Issue 3 — deployment.yaml YAML parse error on helm lint

First helm lint run returned:

  ERROR templates/deployment.yaml: unable to parse YAML:
  error converting YAML to JSON: yaml: line 102:
  did not find expected key

This was a YAML indentation error introduced during copy-paste.
Fixed by replacing the full file contents in VS Code.

### Issue 4 — Pod CrashLoopBackOff on live install

After helm install analytics-api to staging the pod went into
CrashLoopBackOff. kubectl logs showed:

  pydantic_core.ValidationError: 2 validation errors for Settings
  database_url: Field required
  redis_url: Field required

Root cause: analytics-api uses Pydantic Settings which
validates required environment variables at startup. DATABASE_URL
and REDIS_URL are not in the values file — they are intentionally
deferred to Step 11. The app crashed before FastAPI could start,
so the health check got connection refused.

Fix for the live test: added temporary placeholder values to
analytics-api.staging.yaml to unblock the pod start:

  DATABASE_URL: "postgresql://postgres:placeholder@localhost:5432/bebeque"
  REDIS_URL: "redis://localhost:6379"

After confirming the pod reached 1/1 Running, these placeholders
were removed from the values file. The chart is correct. The
secrets wiring is a Step 11 concern.

### Issue 5 — kubectl credentials error after update-kubeconfig

After running aws eks update-kubeconfig, kubectl get nodes
returned:

  error: You must be logged in to the server (the server has
  asked for the client to provide credentials)

Root cause: the EKS cluster uses API_AND_CONFIG_MAP
authentication mode. The IAM user nnenna was not in the
cluster access entries — only the role that ran terraform
apply had access.

Fix: added an EKS access entry for the nnenna IAM user and
associated the AmazonEKSClusterAdminPolicy:

  aws eks create-access-entry \
    --cluster-name bebeque-eks-cluster \
    --principal-arn arn:aws:iam::478544567935:user/nnenna \
    --type STANDARD

  aws eks associate-access-policy \
    --cluster-name bebeque-eks-cluster \
    --principal-arn arn:aws:iam::478544567935:user/nnenna \
    --policy-arn arn:aws:eks::aws:cluster-access-policy/AmazonEKSClusterAdminPolicy \
    --access-scope type=cluster

